1️⃣ World Wide Web Consortium

This is the organization behind:

SVG

HTML

XML

Web standards

Since eForm relies heavily on SVG, W3C would technically be the most aligned standards body.

Pros

Directly related to SVG and web technologies

Strong international recognition

Formal standardization process

Cons

Hard to get something accepted without:

multiple implementations

industry interest

Very slow process

Usually proposals reach W3C after real adoption already exists.

2️⃣ The Document Foundation

This organization maintains:

LibreOffice

OpenDocument Format (ODF) ecosystem

Pros

Very open to document format innovation

Focus on open, long-term readable formats

Community-driven

Easier contact path

Cons

Focused mostly on ODF ecosystem

Not primarily a standards body

Still, this might be the friendliest first place to talk.

3️⃣ OASIS Open

This is actually where ODF was standardized.

Many document standards come from OASIS:

ODF

DocBook

UBL

Pros

Very relevant to document formats

Real standards body

More accessible than W3C

Cons

Requires formal participation for full standardization

4️⃣ Internet Engineering Task Force

This body standardizes internet protocols and formats.

Examples:

HTTP

MIME

JSON-related RFCs

If .eform becomes a MIME type, this is where it would eventually go.

Example future step:

application/eform+zip
🧠 The realistic path most successful formats follow

Most formats become standards in stages:

Publish open specification

Create reference implementation

Get adoption

Then approach a standards body

Examples:

Markdown

PDF

ODF

WebAssembly

All of them existed before standardization.

🚀 What I would recommend for eForm

Your immediate next steps should be:

1. Publish the spec publicly

GitHub repo is perfect.

Include:

spec/
examples/
reference-viewer/
validator/
2. Register a MIME type (later)

Eventually via IETF:

application/eform+zip
3. Create a reference viewer

This is the most important part.

For example:

eform-viewer
eform-cli
eform-js

If people can open .eform, adoption becomes possible.

4. Talk to The Document Foundation first

They are likely to be supportive and curious.

Possible benefits:

feedback

early adoption

possible LibreOffice plugin

📬 Where to contact The Document Foundation

You could reach them through:

mailing lists

LibreOffice dev community

TDF board contact

They are quite approachable.

💡 One more strategic suggestion

Your format is interesting because it combines ideas from:

PDF

SVG

ODF

XForms

It might help to position it as:

"A lightweight open alternative to PDF forms using SVG and JSON."

That framing would make people immediately understand it.

✅ My honest recommendation:

Release eForm 0.5 spec publicly

Build reference viewer

Publish example forms

Then contact The Document Foundation

That’s the most realistic path.
